title: For Sale/Trade:  Japanese Type 38 Series 26 Kokura Arsenal Cavalry Carbine
postcontent:
Price Drop! Again!
Here is the Wikipedia description for my rifle. In the late 30s to early 40s an unknown number of Type38 rifles were converted into "Cavalry Rifles" at Nagoya arsenal, that did all rebuilds of Type 38 and Type 44 rifles and carbines.[10] The barrels were shortened to 635 mm (25.0 in) from the standard 794 mm (31.3 in) barrel and the stock shortened to match the barrel while the handguard retained its original length.[11] The end result is a Type38 which is similar in size to the Type99 Arisaka. The designation as a "Cavalry Rifle" is unusual as at that time the cavalry branch was in decline and it's far more likely these rifles were issued to second line troops instead.[12] There is no consistency to serial numbers or arsenal marks as the rifles were converted from existing stock. Although total production is unknown, it is estimated to have approximately 100,000 converted. 6.5 Japanese is the calibre. The front left ear of the front sight is broken off, but it does still have the original 2400 meter sight from before the conversion. 375 cash/400 trade Also note that the stock is not cracked, it was made that way as they often were in Japan. Also there was never a mum stamped into it as this was issued to a training school as indicated by concentric circles after the serial number.  These received no mums as the Imperial Army rifles did.

title: For Sale:  colt commemorative sam houston 44 caliber
postcontent: This is a beautiful commemorative gun in honor of Sam Houston! Here's a super nice black powder commemorative revolver! Sold by the United States Historical Society, this is the "SAM HOUSTON PISTOL / TEXAS SESQUICENTENNIAL". It is an exact, firing replica of the famous Colt Model 1847 Walker revolver. The Walker revolver was the largest and most powerful repeating black powder handgun ever made. The Walker was named after Captain Samuel Walker, a renowned national hero who fought (and died) in the Texas-Mexico war and who was instrumental in the development of this revolver for use by the early Texas Rangers. This commemorative is dedicated to Sam Houston, the first President of the Texas Republic. Houston was the key figure guiding the destiny of Texas and securing freedom from Mexico. A very large handgun, the Walker tips the scales at nearly five pounds. It fires a .44 caliber bullet and has a 9-inch barrel. The revolver is finished in highly polished blue with lots of 24-karat gold decoration. The cylinder depicts the famous Alamo, has a portrait of Sam Houston, and also a vignette of Houston at the Battle of San Jacinto where his small army defeated Mexico's Santa Anna and secured Texas' independence. Scroll that includes the Texas flag, Texas lone star symbol and other designs adorn the balance of the gun. The smooth walnut grips feature a medallion bearing the likeness of Sam Houston. Condition is excellent, as new, and the revolver remains unfired, the gun is gorgeous! It comes in the specially designed solid walnut case with embossed leather top. The crimson velvet interior of the case is specially fitted for the revolver as well as a powder flask, bullet mold, nipple wrench, and cap tin that is stamped with the outline of Texas. The case is lockable (one key included) and has storage compartments for bullets, etc. Comes with white gloves. Original issue price of this revolver was $2300.00 in the early 1980's. Has a few dings on the wooden box but inside is pristine. Gun is in excellent condition!

title: For Sale:  Nice Shooting Model 1903 S&W Double Action Revolver
location: Santa Fe, NM, New Mexico, United States
postcontent:
S&W Model 1903 Hand Ejector 2nd Change, made in 1905-06. Caliber is .32 S&W or .32 S7W long. (Both fit.)

Yep, some period target grips here! When I got this one, I had every intention to get a set of original or reproduction grips for it. I never did, because they are so darn comfortable. They seem professionally made, and are fitted perfectly. This was going to be my kit gun, but I never get all that much time to roam around in the desert anymore, so it can find a new home. 

It's basically a gray gun, but lockup is tight and it's quite accurate. The patina is pleasant to my eyes, and it has been there and done that for somebody for over a hundred years. It seems to be zeroed for about 40 yards to me, but my son shoots it to point of aim at 25. 

I have only ever shot PPU wadcutters in it, so those loads are very mild. I did take a jackrabbit with it last winter. Aimed at its front elbow, and hit it in the head. My son thinks I am a good pistolero, and I don't ever try to dissuade him. ( In other words, a luck shot.) it's a fun little I-Frame S&W with a 4 1/4 inch barrel.

This is a nice shooting, tight little S&W, At over 100 years old, it's ready to go another hundred.  this ammo is once again readily available locally (Petersons had a BUNCH of it last week.) I can toss in a box of ammo for it for another $25 if you don't feel like going to the store.

Email me through Armslist or call/text at REDACTED to see it in Santa Fe.

Thanks for reading my ad. You will like this little revolver.

Doby Pilgrim
Santa Fe, Nm

title: For Sale:  Sharps Balanced Bolt Carrier Group Complete (BCG) (NP3) AR-15 AR15
postcontent:
•S7 tool steel–When compared to mil spec Carpenter 158, the S7 steel provides a 75% increase in tensile strength and 60% improvement in yield strength.

•Compatible with all existing .223/5.56 variant parts groups and bolt carriers.

•Same weight as standard Milspec M-16 BCG

•NP3 electrodes nickels-based finish

The rounded/tapered lugs push past carbon and debris when the square edges of traditional bolts would typically jam.

Description

With a long history of innovation Sharps Rifle Company (SRC) has done it again!

After developing the most technologically advanced AR-15/M16/M4 bolt in the world Sharps felt compelled to develop a bolt carrier unit to complement it.

We began by identifying what the shortcomings were with the traditional AR-15/M16/M4 bolt carrier. We identified two primary issues. The first being the rotational camming of the carrier during the unlocking portion of the operational cycle. The second being the canting of the bolt carrier group upon firing due to the gas pressure exerted to the gas key which naturally causes the front of the bolt carrier group to rise and the rear of the bolt carrier group to be pressed downward during its rearward travel.

Armed with this knowledge our team of innovative engineers set about to correct those shortcomings. We used computer design technology coupled with real world testing to address both of these issues. When the process was completed we sent the resulting prototypes to a broad spectrum of professionals who use their rifles hard for their personal evaluation and feedback. Their observations were then incorporated into the final design resulting in the new SRC Balanced Bolt Carrier (BBC).

The Sharps BBC is precisely machined from S7 steel which then undergoes our proprietary heat treatment process. Finally the BBC is finished inside and out with NP3 to minimize the need for lubricants, to aid in smooth operation and to make clean up a breeze. The BBC has the SRC logo machine cut on the side of the carrier which is visible when the ejection port door is open. It fits standard AR-15/M16/M4 rifles chambered in .223/5.56mm, 25-45 Sharps and 300 Blackout calibers.

Call 4zero5 4zero6 1665 or email. 

 FTF
